WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.150
Let's understand Conditional Co-Ablation — a method for finding the hidden backup parts of a model's reasoning.

00:00:07.150 --> 00:00:11.310
A language model reads a sentence and predicts the next word.

00:00:11.310 --> 00:00:17.950
Inside, small components called attention heads each carry out a little piece of that computation.

00:00:17.950 --> 00:00:22.170
The few heads that actually drive a behavior are called its circuit.

00:00:22.170 --> 00:00:27.820
To find them, we normally delete one component and watch how much the answer changes.

00:00:27.820 --> 00:00:33.860
But here is the trap. Delete an important head, and a dormant backup silently takes over.

00:00:33.860 --> 00:00:44.320
The answer barely moves — so the deleted head looks unimportant, and the backup, silent before, looks unimportant too. We miss both.

00:00:44.320 --> 00:00:52.470
CoAx asks a smarter question. After we remove the main parts, how much does each remaining unit's effect grow?

00:00:52.470 --> 00:01:00.610
A backup does almost nothing on its own, but a lot once its partner is gone. It needs no labels and no gradients.

00:01:00.610 --> 00:01:08.400
The interactions between heads reveal a hidden module: the main heads and their backups, wired in parallel.

00:01:08.400 --> 00:01:18.950
It works. On a circuit with known backups, CoAx lifts discovery from 0.33 to 0.91, far above every baseline.

00:01:18.950 --> 00:01:25.000
And they really are backups: remove the main heads, and these wake up and start writing the answer.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:30.580
Freezing them undoes the repair — proof that they cause it, not just correlate with it.

00:01:30.580 --> 00:01:40.150
This matters wherever the blind spot hides: attribution, capability removal, and pruning are all repaired by the recovered backups.

00:01:40.150 --> 00:01:49.890
So a component's importance is not fixed — it is conditional. Code, an interactive page, and the paper are linked on screen.
